    <!-- 
        Chosen Palette: Calm Neutrals. A light gray background (bg-slate-100) with dark text (text-slate-800) for readability. Accents of indigo, teal, and amber are used to differentiate thematic sections and highlight key data points.
        Application Structure Plan: A single-page portfolio designed as a narrative journey through the researcher's work. The structure begins with a high-level introduction, followed by an interactive timeline for chronological navigation. The core of the application is organized into thematic research sections (Climate Dynamics, Urbanization, Hazard Assessment) rather than by individual papers. This approach synthesizes and showcases expertise more effectively. Each thematic section combines findings from relevant papers, using interactive charts and key takeaways to tell a compelling story. The application concludes with a skills summary and a publications/contact section. This user flow is designed to guide visitors from a broad overview to specific areas of impact, making complex research accessible and engaging.
        Visualization & Content Choices: 
        1. Texas Climate Trends: Goal: Compare changes. Method: Interactive bar chart (Chart.js) with buttons to filter by variable (Temperature, Precipitation, Humidity). Justification: Allows users to directly compare the magnitude of different climatic shifts identified in the research.
        2. Lubbock Precipitation Forecasting: Goal: Compare model performance. Method: Bar chart (Chart.js) showing Mean Squared Error (MSE) for different models. Justification: Clearly and immediately demonstrates the superior performance of the LSTM model, a key finding of the paper.
        3. Dhaka LULC Change: Goal: Show change over time. Method: Grouped bar chart (Chart.js) visualizing land cover area for three different years. Justification: Effectively illustrates the dramatic increase in urban areas and the decline in vegetation and water bodies.
        4. Cyclone Impact: Goal: Show before-and-after impact. Method: "From-To" matrix using styled HTML/Tailwind, visually representing the land cover transitions (e.g., how much "Agriculture" became "Waterbody"). Justification: More intuitive and impactful than a simple table for showing the scale of transformation.
        5. All visualizations are built using Chart.js on a <canvas> element, with no SVG or Mermaid JS, adhering to technical constraints. Each section includes introductory text to provide context and explain the significance of the findings.
        CONFIRMATION: NO SVG graphics used. NO Mermaid JS used.
    -->
